mology, possibly cognate with Old Norse <i>idh</i> ‘work, activity’.","Cambodian: written អ៊ិត, unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Laird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: status name for a landlord or landowner, from northern Middle English <i>laverd</i> ‘lord’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lard","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Laird  ."]},{"name":"Leard","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Laird  ."]}]},{"name":"Cathcart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Cathcart (Renfrewshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Kithcart","meanings":["English: variant of   Cathcart  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Cathcart 4th Laird Cathcart was born about 1235, in Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Alan Cathcart 3rd Laird Cathcart and NN De Cathcart. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Hendry. He died in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1235–":"umbes 1235–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1269–1309":"1269–1309","124